        {
            "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
            "body": "> perhaps we should consider removing the special nature of cmdwin\r\n\r\nYes, that would be ideal and would remove a ton of code.\r\n\r\n> Is it still needed\r\n\r\nBased on my (very limited) understanding, cmdwin is functionally just a blocking select where you're locked into a pre-populated buffer via various checks in the `normal.c` state machine. So in practice it's similar to the current ui2 pager + some buffer local maps (`<CR>`, `<C-c>`).\r\n\r\n> could we use an approach similar to ui2?\r\n\r\nI don't see why not, but I think maintaining both the current synchronous loop and something like kUICmdwin extension would be a pain. Would the ui2 approach have to live alongside the current code for a while or (since it's less important than cmdline and messages) could it just directly replace it?\r\n\r\nAs it relates to this PR, I think a potential Lua cmdwin would at the very least need a public command preview function and autocommands that run it on `CursorMoved` and `TextChanged`. Would something more portable like that be a good compromise?",
